    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-03-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="178"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3–145</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Director of the Office of Far Eastern
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ballantine</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-02">March 2,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>There is attached for your consideration a tentative list of topics for
                    discussion with Ambassador Hurley.<note n="21" xml:id="d178fn21">Not
                        printed.</note> Some of these topics you may wish to discuss with Mr.
                    Hurley, especially the subject of our policy toward China, and there are
                    attached also for your reference two memoranda, a short one by Mr. Vincent<note
                        n="22" xml:id="d178fn22">March 1, <ref target="#pg_247">p. 247</ref>.</note>
                    dealing with the question of military support to Chinese groups in areas of
                    American military operations and a longer one by Mr. Drumright<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d178fn23">March 2, <ref target="#pg_249">p. 249</ref>.</note> (with
                    contributions by Messrs. Stanton and Vincent) dealing with a wider range of
                    problems. You will of course also wish to consider in this connection the
                    contents of Mr. Atcheson’s telegram no. 324, February 28, 1 p.m.</p>
                <p>I assume that you will wish to delegate to us in FE the discussion of most of the
                    topics in the attached list.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J[<hi rend="smallcaps">oseph</hi>] W. B[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >allantine</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
